.TH "runsvchdir" "8" 
.SH NAME
runsvchdir \- change services directory of runsvdir(8)
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]runsvchdir\f[R] \f[I]dir\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[I]dir\f[R] is a services directory for the use with
\f[B]runsvdir\f[R](8).
If \f[I]dir\f[R] does not start with a slash, it is searched in
\f[B]runsvchdir\f[R]\[aq]s working directory, by default
\f[I]/etc/runit/runsvdir/\f[R].
\f[I]dir\f[R] must not start with a dot.
.PP
\f[B]runsvchdir\f[R] switches to its working directory, copies
\f[I]current\f[R] to \f[I]previous\f[R], and replaces \f[I]current\f[R]
with a symlink pointing to \f[I]dir\f[R].
.PP
Normally \f[I]/service\f[R] is a symlink to \f[I]current\f[R], and
\f[B]runsvdir\f[R](8) is running \f[I]/service/\f[R].
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]RUNSVDIR\f[R]
The environment variable $RUNSVDIR overrides the default working
directory \f[I]/etc/runit/runsvdir/\f[R].
.SH EXIT CODES
\f[B]runsvchdir\f[R] prints an error message and exits 111 on error.
\f[B]runsvchdir\f[R] exits 0 on success.
.SH FILES
/etc/runit/runsvdir/previous
.PD 0
.P
.PD
/etc/runit/runsvdir/current
.PD 0
.P
.PD
/etc/runit/runsvdir/current.new
